er the lesion is suspicious for skin cancer.\n- **Data flow:**  \n  1. Read the image  \n  2. Optionally clean attached metadata/text  \n  3. Send image into the skin-cancer model  \n  4. Compare predictions against labels in evaluation mode  \n  5. Export a summary report\n- **Model/training approach:**  \n  The prototype assumes a pre-trained or fine-tuned skin-cancer vision model is the main inference component.\n- **Evaluation:**  \n  The confusion matrix stage suggests standard supervised evaluation using true/false positives and negatives, which supports metrics like accuracy, precision, recall, and sensitivity.\n- **Deployment/reporting idea:**  \n  The PDF export step implies a lightweight reporting workflow for clinicians, researchers, or QA review.\n\n**Notes**\n- This is a **high-level prototype**, not a full production pipeline.\n- For a real medical workflow, I’d add explicit steps for:\n  - image normalization/resizing\n  - train/validation/test split\n  - augmentation\n  - probability thresholding\n  - calibration\n  - human-review gate\n  - monitoring for drift and false negatives\n\nIf you want, I can also turn this into a **more complete end-to-end pipeline** with training, inference API, and deployment monitoring stages.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0a7b28860b6f9d620169af32cc21748191b9904f83734adf0a\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":522,"output":418,"cacheRead":151424,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":152364,"cost":{"input":0.0013050000000000002,"output":0.00627,"cacheRead":0.037856,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.045431}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773089480630}}
